THE Dar es Salaam Stock Exchange (DSE) equities market slowed down as volume, turnover and prices decreased when winding the Easter week. The weekly turnover and volume declined by 22.34 per cent and 68.80 per cent to 3.94bn/- and 3.49 million shares respectively. However, the stock traded for four days minus Good Friday. Three local counters saw their prices drop led by Swala which went down by 8.16 per cent to 450/-, Nico by 3.28 per cent to 590/- and CRDB Bank by 2.63 per cent to 370/-. DSE was the only stock that appreciated during the week by 5.33 per cent to 1,580/-. Vertex International Securities said in its weekly market review that the equities market started last week with strong performance, but it fell short as the week was shortened by the Easter holiday. “We expect the market to outperform this week as we anticipate companies to post strong 2021 results and possibly a strong first-quarter result from financials,” Vertex said. The self-listed DSE appreciated the most by 5.33 per cent to end the week at 1,580/- per share. Top trading counters for this week were dominated by TBL ticker at 54.95 per cent of the market share, followed by Vodacom at 14.43 per cent, TCCL/Simba cement at 14 per cent and lastly CRDB at 10.67 per cent. Zan Securities said in its weekly market wrap-ups that domestic listed equities have started releasing financial statements with the majority showing promising signs for a lofty dividend payout. “We are going to see more companies releasing their financials and further declaring dividends,” Zan Security report showed. Twiga Cement a year-to-year profit grew by 18.48 per cent to 88.48bn/- and declared a dividend of 390/- per share. Tanga Cement Group reported a net profit of 3.5bn/- last year and walked out of the red of 2.1bn/- in 2020 to end almost four years of losses, but failed to declare a dividend. CRDB last year, the bank at the group level reported a net profit of 267.56bn/- compared to 165.185bn/- in 2020. NMB Bank also made a net profit of 292.14bn/- last year from 210.3bn/- in 2020. Total market capitalisation dropped by 0.47 per cent to 16.04tri/- and domestic market capitalisation went down by 0.29 per cent closing at 10.202tri/-.